00:15:47,580 --> 00:15:49,980
all bashing into each other like a microscopic mosh pit.

228
00:15:50,620 --> 00:15:53,740
Predicting each particle's behaviour is nigh on impossible,

229
00:15:53,740 --> 00:15:57,340
but put enough together and the discontinuities are averaged out,

230
00:15:57,340 --> 00:16:01,020
leaving only the overall movement of the gas in response to external pressures.

231
00:16:02,220 --> 00:16:05,020
There's a video on YouTube where Professor Dan Crisan compares

232
00:16:05,020 --> 00:16:07,740
psychohistory to heat transfer, a similar concept.

233
00:16:08,300 --> 00:16:11,660
At the microscopic level, we have what's called a stochastic process.

234
00:16:12,300 --> 00:16:16,780
Particles with more energy move faster and impart their energy to others through collisions,

235
00:16:16,780 --> 00:16:20,460
but in a given region of this size, these collisions are effectively random.

236
00:16:21,260 --> 00:16:24,300
Again though, zooming out reveals the emergent structure.

237
00:16:24,300 --> 00:16:26,380
Heat flows from hot areas to cold.

238
00:16:27,020 --> 00:16:29,980
At the macroscopic level then, there is a clear pattern in play.

239
00:16:30,780 --> 00:16:34,700
Because there are so many particles, we can assume the system is continuous

240
00:16:34,700 --> 00:16:38,780
and can write expressions known as differential equations to describe that pattern.

241
00:16:38,780 --> 00:16:43,020
The solution to such an equation, if it exists but that's a story for another time,

242
00:16:43,020 --> 00:16:45,500
then describes all those dynamics much more simply.

243
00:16:46,780 --> 00:16:48,620
But there is important nuance here.

244
00:16:49,180 --> 00:16:53,740
The equations assume continuity, that there is no smallest unit of the material,

245
00:16:53,740 --> 00:16:54,940
when in fact we know there is.

246
00:16:55,500 --> 00:16:59,900
Again, in practical terms, the particles are so small that our approximation is fine,

247
00:16:59,900 --> 00:17:04,220
but this does highlight how modellers must be aware of the assumptions inherent in their descriptions.

248
00:17:04,860 --> 00:17:08,380
We assumed that the outside of the material remains at a known temperature,

249
00:17:08,380 --> 00:17:10,860
that the material is of uniform density,

250
00:17:10,860 --> 00:17:15,180
that the laws of physics wouldn't change halfway through via sudden vacuum decay of the universe,

251
00:17:17,100 --> 00:17:19,180
psycho history may not be a law of physics,

252
00:17:19,900 --> 00:17:22,460
but that can't stop the power of mathematical models.

253
00:17:24,460 --> 00:17:29,020
The Prime Minister has announced the most drastic limits to our lives that the UK has

254
00:17:29,580 --> 00:17:31,420
ever seen in living memory.

