320
00:21:03,820 --> 00:21:07,740
One year, a plague, the next near extinction, with no clear pattern.

321
00:21:08,620 --> 00:21:12,060
With admittedly a few documented cases of Lemmings accidentally

322
00:21:12,060 --> 00:21:14,300
driving each other off cliffs during migration,

323
00:21:14,300 --> 00:21:16,620
mass suicide appeared the only explanation.

324
00:21:17,660 --> 00:21:21,420
Though we're still not certain, today we have a much better guess.

325
00:21:21,420 --> 00:21:23,660
Thanks, once again, to mathematics.

326
00:21:24,780 --> 00:21:26,860
This is the Logistic Growth Map.

327
00:21:27,660 --> 00:21:30,540
It's one possible model we can use for animal populations.

328
00:21:31,180 --> 00:21:34,620
The population in year n is represented by xn,

329
00:21:34,620 --> 00:21:38,060
so the equation tells us how to update the population for next year.

330
00:21:38,060 --> 00:21:41,580
i.e. calculate xn plus 1, based on what it was last year.

331
00:21:42,300 --> 00:21:45,660
The term R here represents the basic growth rate,

332
00:21:45,660 --> 00:21:47,740
a measure of how quickly individuals reproduce.

333
00:21:49,260 --> 00:21:51,660
Given an initial population and a growth rate,

334
00:21:51,660 --> 00:21:54,460
we can hit the population with this map over and over again

335
00:21:54,460 --> 00:21:55,980
to see how it develops year on year.

336
00:21:56,620 --> 00:21:58,220
Notice it doesn't grow forever,

337
00:21:58,220 --> 00:22:01,260
as the 1-xn term represents pressure from the environment

338
00:22:01,260 --> 00:22:04,460
for the population to decline, such as a limit on food or space.

339
00:22:04,860 --> 00:22:06,940
You'll notice that for some values of R,

340
00:22:06,940 --> 00:22:09,260
the population eventually reaches a steady state.

341
00:22:09,820 --> 00:22:12,940
After some initial wobbling, it reaches a stable level,

342
00:22:12,940 --> 00:22:16,300
neither growing nor shrinking, as upward and downward pressures are balanced.

343
00:22:17,260 --> 00:22:20,300
For others, it might settle into a repeating pattern,

344
00:22:20,300 --> 00:22:23,420
up one year, down the next, oscillating between two values.

345
00:22:24,460 --> 00:22:26,220
We can plot this behaviour on a graph.

346
00:22:26,780 --> 00:22:29,180
The horizontal axis is the value of R,

347
00:22:29,180 --> 00:22:32,060
the vertical axis is the steady state we eventually reach.

348
00:22:32,700 --> 00:22:36,060
For R less than 1, all populations decline to extinction.

349
00:22:37,340 --> 00:22:41,660
For R between 1 and 3, all populations approach some steady non-zero value.

350
00:22:42,620 --> 00:22:45,340
Beyond 3, populations oscillate between two values.

351
00:22:45,340 --> 00:22:49,660
Extending further, we get oscillations between 4 values and so on.

352
00:22:50,220 --> 00:22:53,660
But beyond about 3.57, something rather silly happens.

353
00:22:54,220 --> 00:22:56,700
The population never approaches a steady value

354
00:22:56,700 --> 00:22:59,660
and instead jumps around unpredictably forever.

355
00:23:00,540 --> 00:23:06,140
And Dr. Ian Malcolm is licking his lips because we've just discovered chaos theory.

356
00:23:07,180 --> 00:23:09,100
Although Jurassic Park might give you the impression

357
00:23:09,100 --> 00:23:12,060
that chaos theory is for the cool kids who aren't doing serious maths,

358
00:23:12,060 --> 00:23:13,900
it is in fact a real field of study.

